<DOC><DOCNO> AP880511-0169 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1337EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Bribes     05-11 0186</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Bribes,0195</SECOND><HEAD>Former Government Official Arrested On Bribery Charges</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Authorities on Wednesday arrested a former officialwho had worked in the prime minister's office and charged him withbribery.   Tokyo prosecutors said Tetsuaki Hashimoto, 58, who was in chargeof the annual budget for government publicity since 1979, allegedlyreceived a total of $800,000 in cash from various advertisingfirms, including $18,400 in bribes from July 1984 to last October.   They said the latter sum was paid in six installments byexecutives of two Tokyo advertising firms handling governmentpublicity.   Arrested for allegedly bribing Hashimoto were MokikichiFukuzawa, 60, president of the Sanko advertising agency, andTatsunori Kawamoto, 59, president of the Nihon Video Networkadvertising firm.   It was the first bribery case involving an official working forthe prime minister since World War II, news reports said.   Hashimoto, who resigned March 1, reportedly handled thegovernment's publicity budget under four prime ministers, includingthe current one, Noboru Takeshita.   The government spent an annual $92 million through March 31 onelectronic media, newspaper and other forms of advertising,according to government statistics.</TEXT></DOC>